    <header>
      <span
        class="author name"
        data-author-provider="twitter"
        data-author-name="Amber C."
        data-author-screen-name="amnicr"
        ><a title="View Amber C. on Twitter" class="twitter" href="https://twitter.com/intent/user?screen_name=amnicr">Amber C.</a></span>
      

      
      <time class="date" data-created-at="2014-05-19T13:51:25.318Z" datetime="2014-05-19T13:51:25.318Z" title="Monday, May 19 2014 1:51 PM"><a href="#comment-ab2e7260-df5c-11e3-8851-e1dc6d03290f">4 months ago</a></time>
      
    </header>

    <span class="text prose"><p>John Green has been one of my all-time favorite authors for years now. I wish most news and blog outlets would at least make mention of his earlier, equally excellent novels - Looking for Alaska, An Abundance of Katherines, Paper Towns. I know the focus right now, with the movie, is on TFIOS though. But all of his fiction really taps into a realistic viewpoint of teenager-dom. He never shies away from being brutally honest, even if it makes you cry.</p>
<p>He got to where he is now by hard work, a quirky fan-base and exceptional writing. I was lucky enough to see him speak in Pittsburgh a few years back at the Carnegie Library and I was blown away by how down-to-earth he is, and how much he cares about the younger generation having a voice. He deserves all the praise he&#39;s getting now, for sure. </p>
</span>

    <footer class="footer">
      
      
